And at the risk of
being Pollyanna,

00:11:57.810 --> 00:12:03.810
I think that there's
progress to be made here

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:04.800
in a bipartisan way.

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:08.610
I think there have been
actions taken by the FDA.

00:12:08.610 --> 00:12:12.090
There are proposals
right now in the Congress

00:12:12.090 --> 00:12:15.720
and being made by the Trump
administration that offer,

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:17.970
I think, reasons for optimism.

00:12:17.970 --> 00:12:20.550
For example, the FDA has
taken a number of actions

00:12:20.550 --> 00:12:23.070
to promote more
competition by easing

00:12:23.070 --> 00:12:26.280
the way for generic
drugs to come to market.

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:29.340
So this includes putting
more money into getting drugs

00:12:29.340 --> 00:12:32.110
onto the market faster.

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:37.200
It involves curbing some
of the practices that

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:42.510
have been used to keep
generic drugs off the market

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:48.330
and limiting the ability
to exploit consumer

00:12:48.330 --> 00:12:50.500
protections and safety.

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:55.750
And so I think that they've
taken some good first steps.

00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:59.400
And there are now
bipartisan proposals

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:02.400
working their way
through the Congress that

00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:03.760
will build on that.

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:07.170
One example is a thing
called the Creates Act, which

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:12.660
is really aimed at taking a
bipartisan approach to curbing

00:13:12.660 --> 00:13:15.420
anti-competitive actions
that make it harder

00:13:15.420 --> 00:13:19.080
for generic drugs to show
that they're bioequivalent,

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:22.830
that they're equally effective.

00:13:22.830 --> 00:13:27.270
And that bill, I think,
is going to come up,

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:30.540
and I'm very optimistic
that it'll pass,

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:31.980
and it will make a difference.

00:13:31.980 --> 00:13:35.950
It will save
billions of dollars.

00:13:35.950 --> 00:13:39.300
A related policy domain is
in the area of competition

00:13:39.300 --> 00:13:41.820
for biologic drugs,
where we have

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:45.720
the possibility of a new
class, a new set of drugs

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:48.810
called biosimilars,
which are like generics,

00:13:48.810 --> 00:13:51.240
but for biological drugs.

00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:56.460
And the FDA has been slow
in getting the regulations

00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:58.270
to bring those to market.

00:13:58.270 --> 00:14:01.470
But there's impatience on
both the Democratic and the

00:14:01.470 --> 00:14:02.730
Republican side.

00:14:02.730 --> 00:14:07.800
And you see us trying to
learn lessons from Europe here

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:09.580
to get those drugs
to market quicker,

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:11.550
and again, save
billions of dollars

00:14:11.550 --> 00:14:14.010
because all the
really expensive drugs

00:14:14.010 --> 00:14:16.380
that you've read about in
the newspaper every day,

00:14:16.380 --> 00:14:18.345
for the most part,
are biologics,

00:14:18.345 --> 00:14:21.830
and so that's a
great place to save.

00:14:21.830 --> 00:14:25.860
A couple of other areas where
I think, in a sense, there's

00:14:25.860 --> 00:14:30.870
low-hanging fruit, one is
anti-gouging legislation.

00:14:30.870 --> 00:14:33.600
There are several bills
in Congress right now.

00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:36.240
I think it's an easy one.

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:38.670
Here we are in the middle
of an opioid crisis,

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:41.880
and we have some of the most
effective drugs being jacked up

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:44.490
about 600% a year.

00:14:44.490 --> 00:14:47.520
And I think that people
on both sides of the aisle

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:49.390
are outraged by that.

00:14:49.390 --> 00:14:53.120
And so I think that
offers a possibility.

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:55.770
And then finally, I think
one of the things that

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:58.440
came through loud and
clear in the election

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:05.880
is that wholesalers,
manufacturers, pharmacy

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:08.850
benefit managers all
make money from the way

00:15:08.850 --> 00:15:10.860
that prices are set.

00:15:10.860 --> 00:15:14.280
The people that get hurt by
the price setting arrangements

00:15:14.280 --> 00:15:16.810
are consumers because
they pay list prices

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:21.730
and don't share in the actual
transaction prices post-rebate.

00:15:21.730 --> 00:15:24.300
And I think, again,
both sides of the aisle

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:27.480
say, we've got to do something
to fix this and allow

00:15:27.480 --> 00:15:33.720
the consumers to share in
the cost-effective gains

00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:34.995
that we've made.

00:15:34.995 --> 00:15:36.870
MARTY KADY: Well,
thanks for your optimism

00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:40.470
in this moment of gridlock.

00:15:40.470 --> 00:15:42.810
It's unusual when the
president, the Republican Senate

00:15:42.810 --> 00:15:45.820
and the House Democrats might
actually agree on something,

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:48.210
so maybe you've got a
more optimistic outlook

00:15:48.210 --> 00:15:49.300
than a lot of folks here.

00:15:49.300 --> 00:15:52.050
Two other health issues we want
to touch on here that came up

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:55.710
in the polls, Americans
are overwhelmingly

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:58.620
concerned with protecting
Medicare and keeping coverage

00:15:58.620 --> 00:16:00.810
for pre-existing conditions.

00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:02.860
This is across the
board rhetorically.

00:16:02.860 --> 00:16:04.680
But as Sheila
knows, when you dig

00:16:04.680 --> 00:16:06.300
into the actual
bills, especially

00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:07.758
some of the Republican
bills, there

00:16:07.758 --> 00:16:11.340
are some cheaper sort of
off-brand insurance plans

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:15.037
that might not cover
pre-existing conditions.

00:16:15.037 --> 00:16:17.370
Sheila, can you talk a little
about those two priorities

00:16:17.370 --> 00:16:18.820
and what you expect to see here?

00:16:18.820 --> 00:16:21.870
And feel free to cover Congress,
executive action, wherever you

00:16:21.870 --> 00:16:23.610
see the roadmap ahead on this.

00:16:23.610 --> 00:16:25.470
SHEILA BURKE: Thanks
so much, Marty,

00:16:25.470 --> 00:16:27.660
and thanks for
including me today.

00:16:27.660 --> 00:16:30.750
Medicare, as Bob knows and
Richard certainly knows,

00:16:30.750 --> 00:16:34.530
remains enormously popular
among the American public.

00:16:34.530 --> 00:16:37.080
And it is approached
with great caution

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:40.800
by both sides of the
aisle and both bodies.

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:43.230
While the House leadership,
the new leadership

00:16:43.230 --> 00:16:46.170
is inevitably going to raise
a number of the suggestions

00:16:46.170 --> 00:16:49.740
about Medicare buy-ins
and Medicare for all,

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:52.380
and will no doubt try and
respond to those issues that

00:16:52.380 --> 00:16:54.910
arose during the
course of the election,

00:16:54.910 --> 00:16:57.750
I think it is unlikely
that any major moves will

00:16:57.750 --> 00:16:59.970
be made with respect
to the Medicare program

00:16:59.970 --> 00:17:02.070
on either side of the aisle.

00:17:02.070 --> 00:17:06.190
Unfortunately or fortunately,
we are already in the '20 cycle,

00:17:06.190 --> 00:17:09.700
so people are already looking
towards the '20 elections.

00:17:09.700 --> 00:17:12.510
And I think they approach
Medicare and the suggestion

00:17:12.510 --> 00:17:14.160
of doing anything
to Medicare that

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:19.200
will alter it any dramatic way
essentially will fall flat.

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:22.079
But I think there is going to
be real focus on strengthening

00:17:22.079 --> 00:17:23.819
the program, and
I think there'll

00:17:23.819 --> 00:17:27.480
be discussions that take
place about what might one

00:17:27.480 --> 00:17:30.510
do with respect to the current
structure of the program, which

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:34.290
has remained largely
intact since 1965?

00:17:34.290 --> 00:17:38.190
Certainly incremental changes
may well be discussed.

00:17:38.190 --> 00:17:40.070
Drugs, as Richard has suggested.

00:17:40.070 --> 00:17:42.090
There is a big piece
of the Medicare program

00:17:42.090 --> 00:17:44.700
and a lot of the discussion
around drug reform, which

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:48.070
has to do with the cost of
drugs to Medicare beneficiaries.

00:17:48.070 --> 00:17:50.560
So we already know the
administration and the Congress

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:52.830
has begun to look at
some of those questions

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:55.170
around negotiation,
around the price point,

00:17:55.170 --> 00:17:57.390
around rebate strategies.

00:17:57.390 --> 00:17:59.100
But there are also
other elements

00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:00.780
of the Medicare program
that people have

00:18:00.780 --> 00:18:02.430
talked about strengthening.

00:18:02.430 --> 00:18:04.650
There are a bucket of things
that Medicare does not

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:07.800
currently cover that people
have suggested really

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:11.550
need to be added to the program,
issues around dental coverage,

00:18:11.550 --> 00:18:15.710
interestingly enough, vision
coverage, hearing coverage.

00:18:15.710 --> 00:18:17.700
And really, the
out-of-pocket costs,

00:18:17.700 --> 00:18:20.520
because there's no real
catastrophic protection

00:18:20.520 --> 00:18:23.410
for folks that are in the
traditional Medicare program.

00:18:23.410 --> 00:18:25.110
So I think there'll
be attention given

00:18:25.110 --> 00:18:28.680
to some of those issues by
Democrats and Republicans.

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:31.680
I also think there'll be
efforts to try and simplify

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:32.670
the program.

00:18:32.670 --> 00:18:35.820
The Medicare Advantage Program,
which is the managed care

00:18:35.820 --> 00:18:38.640
piece of the program,
now has about 30%

00:18:38.640 --> 00:18:41.370
of the population enrolled
in those programs,

00:18:41.370 --> 00:18:45.210
and there are questions about
simplifying that program, about

00:18:45.210 --> 00:18:47.910
access issues, issues
like telehealth,

00:18:47.910 --> 00:18:50.550
and other opportunities to
essentially make services

00:18:50.550 --> 00:18:52.630
more readily available.

00:18:52.630 --> 00:18:55.500
One of the other interesting
questions that may arise

00:18:55.500 --> 00:18:59.820
are over the historic Stark
rules about, essentially,

00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:02.280
the protections under
HIPAA and Stark,

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:05.760
and whether they are inhibiting
the development of organized

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:06.810
programs.

00:19:06.810 --> 00:19:08.730
Both the administration
and many others

00:19:08.730 --> 00:19:11.610
are interested in getting
Medicare beneficiaries

00:19:11.610 --> 00:19:14.280
into organized systems
of care, believing

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:16.230
that coordinated
care, in fact, will

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:19.980
improve the health of our
elderly and disabled citizens,

00:19:19.980 --> 00:19:22.770
so there'll be attention to
those kinds of questions.

00:19:22.770 --> 00:19:26.610
Senator Grassley, the incoming
chairman of the Senate Finance

00:19:26.610 --> 00:19:29.400
Committee who had been
chairman previously,

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:32.520
has a long-standing
interest in oversight,

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:34.530
and has indicated
already his interest

00:19:34.530 --> 00:19:36.330
in looking at the
Medicare program,

00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:38.430
looking at fraud
and abuse, looking

00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:40.170
at the cost of the program.

00:19:40.170 --> 00:19:42.510
I fully expect he will do that.

00:19:42.510 --> 00:19:44.310
Incoming chairman
of Ways and Means

00:19:44.310 --> 00:19:47.070
Mr. Neil has also
indicated interest

00:19:47.070 --> 00:19:49.290
in looking at
oversight, but also

00:19:49.290 --> 00:19:51.780
interest in looking at what
the administration is doing

00:19:51.780 --> 00:19:54.840
in terms of demonstrations,
with respect to the Medicare

00:19:54.840 --> 00:19:57.540
and Medicaid programs, for
particularly the Medicare

00:19:57.540 --> 00:20:00.690
program, and wanting
greater transparency over

00:20:00.690 --> 00:20:02.790
what, in fact, might occur.

00:20:02.790 --> 00:20:06.730
With respect to, essentially,
preexisting conditions

00:20:06.730 --> 00:20:11.080
in sort of my short comments, a
couple of things come to mind.

00:20:11.080 --> 00:20:14.400
One is people are increasingly
sensitive to the increasing

00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:16.150
number of the uninsured.

00:20:16.150 --> 00:20:20.980
We're upwards of 13.7% or
almost 14% now uninsured,

00:20:20.980 --> 00:20:22.900
so those numbers are going up.

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:24.510
So the question
about preexisting,

00:20:24.510 --> 00:20:27.090
the question about
coverage availability

00:20:27.090 --> 00:20:29.040
is one that, in
fact, is of concern

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:30.850
on both sides of the aisle.

00:20:30.850 --> 00:20:34.020
As Bob has suggested, deep
divisions over the fundamentals

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:35.310
of the ACA.

00:20:35.310 --> 00:20:37.410
Of course, we have
the Texas court case,

00:20:37.410 --> 00:20:41.580
which has called into question
the fundamentals of the ACA,

00:20:41.580 --> 00:20:44.980
although it is on pause,
as a result, frankly,

00:20:44.980 --> 00:20:47.500
of the shutdown.

00:20:47.500 --> 00:20:50.160
But on January the 29th,
the Ways and Means Committee

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:52.470
has scheduled a
hearing on oversight,

00:20:52.470 --> 00:20:55.530
essentially looking at the
preexisting condition issue,

00:20:55.530 --> 00:20:57.660
looking at what those
solutions might be.

00:20:57.660 --> 00:21:01.470
And it is the one piece
where, in fact, both Democrats

00:21:01.470 --> 00:21:04.260
and Republicans seem to
have an interest in finding

00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:07.980
a resolution as to what
one might do with that.

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:10.860
The president has sent
sort of mixed signals.

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:12.490
He wants to be sure
they're covered.

00:21:12.490 --> 00:21:16.210
But then, of course, they put
forward the short-term plans,

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:18.090
which will be
permitted to avoid any

00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:20.220
of the requirements in the ACA.

00:21:20.220 --> 00:21:22.290
So those questions,
the questions

00:21:22.290 --> 00:21:26.580
of what the administration is
doing on a regulatory basis, as

00:21:26.580 --> 00:21:30.060
well as legislative attempts
to try and fix that issue,

00:21:30.060 --> 00:21:31.740
I think, will be on
the agenda for both

00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:33.376
the House and the Senate.

00:21:33.376 --> 00:21:34.500
MARTY KADY: Thanks, Sheila.

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:37.590
And we'll be coming back to a
lot of the politics of the ACA

00:21:37.590 --> 00:21:40.650
in the future as
this panel goes on.

00:21:40.650 --> 00:21:44.040
But we're going to
shift to education here.

00:21:44.040 --> 00:21:47.130
Another perhaps a bright
spot in the poll in a country

00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:49.440
so bitterly divided
over politics,

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:52.350
there was some unity on
increasing spending on K

00:21:52.350 --> 00:21:55.560
through 12 education, on
funding for community college,

00:21:55.560 --> 00:22:00.240
and overwhelming concern
about student debt.

00:22:00.240 --> 00:22:01.380
That's where there's unity.

00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:03.570
The tactics on
what to do about it

00:22:03.570 --> 00:22:05.910
is where it sort of falls apart.

00:22:05.910 --> 00:22:07.606
Martin, thanks for
coming on here.

00:22:07.606 --> 00:22:08.730
You're an education expert.

00:22:08.730 --> 00:22:11.220
What's the outlook for Congress
and the executive branch

00:22:11.220 --> 00:22:13.674
on education policy on
these various topics?

00:22:13.674 --> 00:22:15.340
MARTIN WEST: Well,
thanks for having me.

00:22:15.340 --> 00:22:18.270
Let me start with the issue
of increasing spending

00:22:18.270 --> 00:22:21.930
on K12 education where despite
the very interesting poll

00:22:21.930 --> 00:22:24.750
results, I think you're
very unlikely to see much

00:22:24.750 --> 00:22:26.730
in the way of
substantive change.

00:22:26.730 --> 00:22:29.190
Major changes to
federal spending

00:22:29.190 --> 00:22:31.620
on discretionary
programs like education

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:37.251
tend to happen in the context of
major reauthorizations of laws,

00:22:37.251 --> 00:22:39.000
like the Every Student
Succeeds Act, which

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.710
governs federal involvement
in K12 education.

00:22:41.710 --> 00:22:43.670
And while that
law is technically

00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:45.210
up for reauthorization
this year,

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:48.120
there is absolutely zero
appetite in Congress

00:22:48.120 --> 00:22:52.110
to revisit what was a very
hard-won bipartisan compromise

00:22:52.110 --> 00:22:53.910
in 2015.

00:22:53.910 --> 00:22:56.220
And I think the overall
budget picture, which

00:22:56.220 --> 00:22:58.590
includes the threat
of sequestration cuts

00:22:58.590 --> 00:23:00.540
if there there's no
new budget agreement,

00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:03.150
means that those who are
pushing for increases

00:23:03.150 --> 00:23:05.190
in any discretionary
spending category

00:23:05.190 --> 00:23:07.890
have very, very little leverage.

00:23:07.890 --> 00:23:11.470
Now, in making that prediction,
I should note two caveats.

00:23:11.470 --> 00:23:13.830
One is that I do think
the poll results help

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:17.400
us understand why despite calls
from Republicans to reduce

00:23:17.400 --> 00:23:19.980
the federal footprint in
education, to even eliminate

00:23:19.980 --> 00:23:22.950
the Department of Education,
after two years of unified

00:23:22.950 --> 00:23:25.080
Republican control,
you actually haven't

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:29.220
seen a decrease in federal
spending on education.

00:23:29.220 --> 00:23:31.830
Education's actually fared quite
well over the past two years,

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:33.492
from a budget perspective.

00:23:33.492 --> 00:23:35.700
And I think that's because
cutting education spending

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:38.730
at any level of government is
just not a political winner

00:23:38.730 --> 00:23:39.259
right now.

00:23:39.259 --> 00:23:40.800
And that's what I
think you're seeing

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:42.870
reflected in the poll results.

00:23:42.870 --> 00:23:45.720
And the second caveat is
that it's very important

00:23:45.720 --> 00:23:48.780
to keep in mind that the
federal government is just

00:23:48.780 --> 00:23:52.370
a 10% investor or
less in K12 education.

00:23:52.370 --> 00:23:56.280
And so that means even any
very substantial increase

00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:59.850
or reduction in federal
spending on K12 education

00:23:59.850 --> 00:24:03.300
doesn't really translate
into a major change

00:24:03.300 --> 00:24:07.770
in the level of resources
available in a given school.

00:24:07.770 --> 00:24:10.380
As in most aspects of
our education system,

00:24:10.380 --> 00:24:13.150
the real action is at the
state and local level,

00:24:13.150 --> 00:24:15.840
and you have seen
increased activism

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:19.030
around issues of school
funding and teacher salaries

00:24:19.030 --> 00:24:21.930
in the past year that
we can return to later.

00:24:21.930 --> 00:24:25.050
Now, on student loans,
I think it's important

00:24:25.050 --> 00:24:28.380
here to distinguish between
efforts to reduce the debt

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:32.040
load of former students
who are currently repaying

00:24:32.040 --> 00:24:35.430
loans and efforts to fix the
student loan system going

00:24:35.430 --> 00:24:36.360
forward.

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:39.660
The former may be
a desirable goal,

00:24:39.660 --> 00:24:42.810
particularly as concerns
mount that debt loads may

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:44.070
be holding back the economy.

00:24:44.070 --> 00:24:46.680
And I suspect you'll hear
Democratic presidential

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:50.880
candidates talking about that
a lot on the campaign trail.

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:54.700
But it does nothing to
increase access for students

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:56.830
to higher education
going forward.

00:24:56.830 --> 00:24:59.977
On the latter, this question
of actually increasing access,

00:24:59.977 --> 00:25:01.810
I think the big question
is whether Congress

00:25:01.810 --> 00:25:03.393
is going to be able
to reach agreement

00:25:03.393 --> 00:25:06.040
on a reauthorization of
the Higher Education Act.

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:09.250
And there, the major player
is Senator Lamar Alexander

00:25:09.250 --> 00:25:10.070
from Tennessee.

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:13.270
He's a former Secretary of
Education, former university

00:25:13.270 --> 00:25:14.080
president.

00:25:14.080 --> 00:25:16.240
He's recently announced
that he's not running

00:25:16.240 --> 00:25:18.490
for re-election in 2020.

00:25:18.490 --> 00:25:20.920
He wants to go out
with a legacy bill,

00:25:20.920 --> 00:25:24.250
and this would be the
opportunity to do that.

00:25:24.250 --> 00:25:25.960
He's made, I think,
good progress

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:28.180
in creating some
bipartisan consensus

00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:30.880
around the goal of simplifying
the federal financial aid

00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:34.150
system and creating some
accountability for colleges

00:25:34.150 --> 00:25:36.880
by putting them on the hook
if their students don't

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:39.310
repay their loans.

00:25:39.310 --> 00:25:43.660
I think the big question then is
whether the areas where there's

00:25:43.660 --> 00:25:47.230
not bipartisan consensus,
questions like campus safety,

00:25:47.230 --> 00:25:49.090
and sexual assault,
federal regulation,

00:25:49.090 --> 00:25:51.190
all that under Title
IX, whether they

00:25:51.190 --> 00:25:53.500
will get in the
way of the ability

00:25:53.500 --> 00:25:56.235
to reach a deal going forward.

00:25:56.235 --> 00:25:57.610
The other prediction
that I think

00:25:57.610 --> 00:26:00.760
it's very safe to make with
respect to the new Congress

00:26:00.760 --> 00:26:03.010
is just that you'll see
a ramped up oversight

00:26:03.010 --> 00:26:05.917
function in the House
of Representatives

00:26:05.917 --> 00:26:07.750
with respect to the
Department of Education.

00:26:07.750 --> 00:26:10.960
So incoming chair of the
Education and Labor Committee,

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:14.262
Bobby Scott from Virginia,
has indicated that he's

00:26:14.262 --> 00:26:15.470
going to be holding hearings.

00:26:15.470 --> 00:26:17.890
He's going to be
requesting information

00:26:17.890 --> 00:26:19.870
from the department,
particularly with respect

00:26:19.870 --> 00:26:22.570
to issues of civil rights
protections in schools,

00:26:22.570 --> 00:26:25.137
and the regulation of
for-profit colleges.

00:26:25.137 --> 00:26:27.220
These are areas where the
Trump administration has

00:26:27.220 --> 00:26:29.800
made some significant changes
through executive action

00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:31.990
to Obama-era
policies, and I think

00:26:31.990 --> 00:26:35.710
you'll see a lot of examination
of those areas over the months

00:26:35.710 --> 00:26:36.505
to come.

00:26:36.505 --> 00:26:38.240
MARTY KADY: Well,
as you've heard--

00:26:38.240 --> 00:26:40.420
thank you, Martin--
the student loan debt

00:26:40.420 --> 00:26:42.430
is a big burden
for many Americans.

00:26:42.430 --> 00:26:44.290
We've got another clip here.

00:26:44.290 --> 00:26:47.620
This clip is from the
nonprofit Student Debt Crisis.

