00:28:12.470 --> 00:28:14.990
And would that
impact this at all,

00:28:14.990 --> 00:28:17.625
or are there other innovative
ideas around student debt?

00:28:17.625 --> 00:28:20.000
I think that's an important
topic, especially in a higher

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:20.810
education setting here.

00:28:20.810 --> 00:28:21.560
MARTIN WEST: Yeah.

00:28:21.560 --> 00:28:24.320
I think it's important as we
start talking about the student

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:25.820
debt issue to make
sure that we have

00:28:25.820 --> 00:28:29.150
a good understanding of where
the problem is most severe.

00:28:29.150 --> 00:28:30.770
And it turns out
that if you look

00:28:30.770 --> 00:28:33.650
at who's struggling in terms
of repayment, who's defaulting

00:28:33.650 --> 00:28:35.480
on their student
loans, it's generally

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:38.900
not those borrowers who
have significant debts,

00:28:38.900 --> 00:28:42.200
those who have borrowed to
go to a four-year school,

00:28:42.200 --> 00:28:44.690
especially those who borrow
to go to graduate school, who

00:28:44.690 --> 00:28:47.090
tend to have the
largest debt loads,

00:28:47.090 --> 00:28:50.150
and ultimately tend to be
very successful economically,

00:28:50.150 --> 00:28:52.890
and to be able to manage
that repayment burden.

00:28:52.890 --> 00:28:56.450
Where the problem is
most severe is people

00:28:56.450 --> 00:28:58.820
who have very modest
loan amounts, generally

00:28:58.820 --> 00:29:03.560
under $20,000, who have borrowed
to attend a career training

00:29:03.560 --> 00:29:05.750
program, maybe in the
for-profit sector,

00:29:05.750 --> 00:29:07.820
have failed to complete
it, failed to transition

00:29:07.820 --> 00:29:08.640
into the workforce.

00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:10.098
And they're the
ones who are really

00:29:10.098 --> 00:29:11.930
defaulting on their loans.

00:29:11.930 --> 00:29:15.380
And so I think the reason it's
important to keep that in mind

00:29:15.380 --> 00:29:19.040
is that any sort of across
the board debt relief proposal

00:29:19.040 --> 00:29:23.280
is likely to be quite regressive
in its impact ultimately.

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:24.910
And so I think
that's where there's

00:29:24.910 --> 00:29:28.250
a need for some creative
thinking, as you say.

00:29:28.250 --> 00:29:31.250
The idea that's really
emerged in higher education

00:29:31.250 --> 00:29:33.110
over the past
couple of decades is

00:29:33.110 --> 00:29:36.110
the idea of income-contingent
repayment plans.

00:29:36.110 --> 00:29:39.170
So basing the amount
that you repay

00:29:39.170 --> 00:29:41.450
to some degree on your income.

00:29:41.450 --> 00:29:46.550
And this would target assistance
where it's most needed.

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:49.010
The reason it makes sense
from an economic perspective

00:29:49.010 --> 00:29:52.820
is that college is generally
still a very good investment.

00:29:52.820 --> 00:29:54.920
Most people, as a
result, are able to repay

00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:58.950
that loan that they borrow, but
it's also a risky investment.

00:29:58.950 --> 00:30:03.615
And so I think this is a
good way to manage that risk.

00:30:03.615 --> 00:30:05.240
If it doesn't pay
off for you, then you

00:30:05.240 --> 00:30:09.950
end up paying back less, and are
less likely to go into default.

00:30:09.950 --> 00:30:12.320
You saw a big expansion
in the availability

00:30:12.320 --> 00:30:15.860
of income-based repayment plans
under the Obama administration.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:18.230
And interestingly,
this isn't an area

00:30:18.230 --> 00:30:21.440
where you've seen the Trump
administration roll back

00:30:21.440 --> 00:30:23.180
those programs.

00:30:23.180 --> 00:30:26.420
I think in the context of
a potential congressional

00:30:26.420 --> 00:30:28.640
reauthorization of the
Higher Education Act,

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:31.544
you would see an attempt to
really simplify and streamline

00:30:31.544 --> 00:30:33.710
the various options that
are available to borrowers.

00:30:33.710 --> 00:30:36.020
They're ridiculously
confusing right now.

00:30:36.020 --> 00:30:40.480
They require you to recertify
your eligibility year to year,

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:43.652
and so they're not as widely
used as they should be already.

00:30:43.652 --> 00:30:45.110
And so I think
that's an area where

00:30:45.110 --> 00:30:46.782
you'd see a lot of thought.

00:30:46.782 --> 00:30:48.920
MARTY KADY: Well,
thank you, Martin.

00:30:48.920 --> 00:30:51.110
Great review on student debt.

00:30:51.110 --> 00:30:52.930
Let's go back to Sheila.

00:30:52.930 --> 00:30:57.770
To pick up on something you
mentioned, the ACA lawsuit.

00:30:57.770 --> 00:31:01.760
Basically, the entire ACA was
thrown out by a Texas judge

00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:03.230
back in mid-December.

00:31:03.230 --> 00:31:06.060
It's caught up in
the courts now,

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:10.130
and I think a lot of people
were caught off-guard with that.

00:31:10.130 --> 00:31:12.080
It was thrown on a
technicality, but that

00:31:12.080 --> 00:31:14.180
was an ideological
decision, but one

00:31:14.180 --> 00:31:18.440
that still reveals the ongoing
legal fragility of Obamacare.

00:31:18.440 --> 00:31:22.714
We're almost 10 years into this
law, and it's extraordinary,

00:31:22.714 --> 00:31:24.380
I think, to people
who don't follow this

00:31:24.380 --> 00:31:30.232
that a lower court judge can
try to toss the entire law out.

00:31:30.232 --> 00:31:31.940
And it'll go through
the courts, but what

00:31:31.940 --> 00:31:34.249
is your outlook on that and
any other legal challenges

00:31:34.249 --> 00:31:34.790
to Obamacare?

00:31:34.790 --> 00:31:36.248
I know one of the
questions pending

00:31:36.248 --> 00:31:39.020
from our online audience is
whether Obamacare is here

00:31:39.020 --> 00:31:40.890
to stay.

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:42.740
I don't know the
answer, but maybe you

00:31:42.740 --> 00:31:44.411
can jump in there a little bit.

00:31:44.411 --> 00:31:46.910
SHEILA BURKE: I'm not sure any
of us really know the answer.

00:31:46.910 --> 00:31:49.690
I mean, I guess I would posit
that it is, in fact, here

00:31:49.690 --> 00:31:51.060
to stay.

00:31:51.060 --> 00:31:54.310
But, in fact, the court case
did catch us by surprise.

00:31:54.310 --> 00:31:56.250
It, of course, is
being appealed.

00:31:56.250 --> 00:32:00.230
The appeal is obviously
on hold while we're

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:03.160
in this break period.

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:05.760
But I think there is an
ongoing set of challenges.

00:32:05.760 --> 00:32:07.710
Certainly, there are
the court challenges

00:32:07.710 --> 00:32:09.060
which are being appealed.

00:32:09.060 --> 00:32:10.740
But there's also
the ongoing efforts

00:32:10.740 --> 00:32:12.990
on the part of the
administration,

00:32:12.990 --> 00:32:15.180
with respect to the
program that occur

00:32:15.180 --> 00:32:18.060
in a regulatory or
an administrative way

00:32:18.060 --> 00:32:20.220
that we continue to see,
whether it's shortening

00:32:20.220 --> 00:32:23.760
the period of enrollment,
whether it is basically

00:32:23.760 --> 00:32:27.390
ceasing the funding for much
of the outreach activities.

00:32:27.390 --> 00:32:30.450
So there's no question that
there are efforts going on

00:32:30.450 --> 00:32:32.340
and will continue to take place.

00:32:32.340 --> 00:32:34.860
At the same time, I think
there is an acknowledgment

00:32:34.860 --> 00:32:37.230
that there are
elements of the ACA,

00:32:37.230 --> 00:32:40.740
have they been given the
opportunity to repair or to fix

00:32:40.740 --> 00:32:43.500
the original legislation,
that folks would

00:32:43.500 --> 00:32:45.690
have liked to have go forward.

00:32:45.690 --> 00:32:48.480
There is an obvious question
as to the benefit structure

00:32:48.480 --> 00:32:50.640
in the ACA, and the
fullness of the benefits,

00:32:50.640 --> 00:32:53.200
and whether, in fact, that
ought to be revisited.

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:55.770
But I think we will continue
to see this tension.

00:32:55.770 --> 00:32:58.620
Obviously, with the House
now under Democratic control,

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:00.360
you won't see the
same kind of pressure

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:03.090
that you saw from
the House Republicans

00:33:03.090 --> 00:33:06.300
essentially pursuing
legislation and moving it.

00:33:06.300 --> 00:33:09.559
The Senate has chosen not
to pursue much of that work.

00:33:09.559 --> 00:33:11.850
But I think you have to assume
that there will continue

00:33:11.850 --> 00:33:13.680
to be issues that arise.

00:33:13.680 --> 00:33:15.120
There are also
issues taking place

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:17.700
at the state level with
a number of states not

00:33:17.700 --> 00:33:21.360
only in the case of this court
case, but a number of states

00:33:21.360 --> 00:33:24.510
that are seeking ways and
waivers to essentially do

00:33:24.510 --> 00:33:27.600
a number of things, whether it's
with their Medicaid program,

00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:30.780
or whether it's restructuring
their benefit structure,

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:33.160
or restructuring their
insurance market.

00:33:33.160 --> 00:33:36.210
So I think we have to assume
those conversations will

00:33:36.210 --> 00:33:37.995
continue to take place.

00:33:37.995 --> 00:33:39.380
MARTY KADY: Thanks, Sheila.

00:33:39.380 --> 00:33:41.010
Richard, I want
to go back to you.

00:33:41.010 --> 00:33:43.140
On the question of
drug pricing, I'm

00:33:43.140 --> 00:33:45.371
curious about what the
industry's approach is

00:33:45.371 --> 00:33:45.870
going to be.

00:33:45.870 --> 00:33:47.661
They're going to get
hauled up to the Hill,

00:33:47.661 --> 00:33:51.930
and Democrats certainly love to
have pharmaceutical executives

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:55.290
up there taking the
oath and being asked

00:33:55.290 --> 00:33:58.880
why insulin costs so much.

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:01.560
So can you talk a little
bit about industry strategy

00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:05.067
when it comes to dealing with
the politics of drug prices?

00:34:05.067 --> 00:34:06.150
RICHARD FRANK: Well, yeah.

00:34:06.150 --> 00:34:08.880
We just saw a
report that came out

00:34:08.880 --> 00:34:14.100
that well I guess this past year
has been the biggest lobbying

00:34:14.100 --> 00:34:16.506
expenditure year
in quite a while.

00:34:16.506 --> 00:34:17.880
I think it was
around $26 million

00:34:17.880 --> 00:34:22.030
was spent by big
pharma lobbying.

00:34:22.030 --> 00:34:25.320
So clearly, they're not
standing still for this.

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:31.080
And I do think the
actual picture has

00:34:31.080 --> 00:34:33.210
gotten more complicated.

00:34:33.210 --> 00:34:37.440
I mentioned earlier that there
is this concern about why

00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:40.230
is it that everybody
is making money

00:34:40.230 --> 00:34:42.370
on the backs of consumers?

00:34:42.370 --> 00:34:48.389
And I think the entire way
that we've organized our supply

00:34:48.389 --> 00:34:52.469
chain and the way we
put prices and discounts

00:34:52.469 --> 00:34:58.890
through the system has
created enormous complexity

00:34:58.890 --> 00:35:05.010
and opportunities for our
firms with market power

00:35:05.010 --> 00:35:07.080
all the way down
through the supply chain

00:35:07.080 --> 00:35:10.290
to make lots of money while
the consumers are paying prices

00:35:10.290 --> 00:35:13.680
that are way out of line with
what any of the other players

00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:14.790
are paying.

00:35:14.790 --> 00:35:16.810
And so I think that's
going to be a concern.

00:35:16.810 --> 00:35:21.420
And I think actually, efforts to
fix that will probably receive

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:24.420
some support from the industry.

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:26.880
And so that's,
again, a common point

00:35:26.880 --> 00:35:32.070
where you can triangulate all
the players mostly falling

00:35:32.070 --> 00:35:33.270
on the side of fixing that.

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:35.680
MARTY KADY: Trump is very
unpredictable, as we all know.

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:40.260
Do you see him doing something
unilaterally on drug prices

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:42.810
to make substantive
and political point?

00:35:42.810 --> 00:35:47.670
RICHARD FRANK: Well, there's
this issue around his desire

00:35:47.670 --> 00:35:53.430
to introduce European
prices into the Medicare

00:35:53.430 --> 00:35:56.920
program for
physician-administered drugs.

00:35:56.920 --> 00:36:01.530
And I think that is
an important signal

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:05.250
because much like the
Obama administration,

00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:09.690
it represents an effort to
separate how you pay doctors

00:36:09.690 --> 00:36:11.190
from how you buy drugs.

00:36:11.190 --> 00:36:15.270
And so that's an
important debate to have.

00:36:15.270 --> 00:36:20.370
The actual specifics of the
use of international prices

00:36:20.370 --> 00:36:25.650
to set prices here is, I
think, less clear and much more

00:36:25.650 --> 00:36:26.490
controversial.

00:36:26.490 --> 00:36:29.160
And so whether we will
actually land there,

00:36:29.160 --> 00:36:33.150
I think probably we won't.

00:36:33.150 --> 00:36:34.860
But I think having
a conversation

00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:38.400
about rearranging the way we
pay for physician-administered

00:36:38.400 --> 00:36:41.035
drugs is important and
will probably happen.

00:36:41.035 --> 00:36:42.780
MARTY KADY: Thanks.

