or previous polls
that you've done

00:37:07.460 --> 00:37:09.680
show where the
breakdown happens.

00:37:13.390 --> 00:37:16.640
ROBERT BLENDON: This is
important generically

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:19.040
for people to recognize.

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:22.190
When people often
answer polls, they

00:37:22.190 --> 00:37:25.640
expect preferences
about principles.

00:37:25.640 --> 00:37:28.250
I want something done
about drug prices.

00:37:28.250 --> 00:37:32.270
When they learn about what
it is, they come apart.

00:37:32.270 --> 00:37:35.690
And so there's a real
division about whether or not

00:37:35.690 --> 00:37:38.500
we should encourage just more
market competition on the drug

00:37:38.500 --> 00:37:39.000
side.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.630
People just believe for this.

00:37:41.630 --> 00:37:44.030
At the other side are people,
let's get the government

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:46.370
across from the
pharmaceutical industry.

00:37:46.370 --> 00:37:50.600
And basically, a
negotiation is a nice word

00:37:50.600 --> 00:37:53.390
for somewhat more
price controls.

00:37:53.390 --> 00:37:55.550
And so one side,
you split exactly

00:37:55.550 --> 00:37:58.710
on what you do about that.

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:04.580
So a lot of these policies,
and the answer is taxes.

00:38:04.580 --> 00:38:09.180
When asked about, should public
school teachers be paid more,

00:38:09.180 --> 00:38:11.900
73% of people said absolutely.

00:38:11.900 --> 00:38:13.034
Those teachers are right.

00:38:13.034 --> 00:38:14.450
And then just the
simple question,

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:20.810
would you pay more taxes to do
that, half said no for that.

00:38:20.810 --> 00:38:24.560
So these divisions about
how the policies are--

00:38:24.560 --> 00:38:27.080
and it wouldn't be as
difficult if people

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:28.790
didn't separate by party.

00:38:28.790 --> 00:38:31.860
That is, if you didn't go to
a different clubhouse, you--

00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:34.210
but now, if I don't
want to pay those taxes,

00:38:34.210 --> 00:38:37.740
I'm in the party of
no taxes for that.

00:38:37.740 --> 00:38:39.800
So a lot of these
issues come apart

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:42.720
not only because of the
lobbying that goes on,

00:38:42.720 --> 00:38:47.840
but because how to solve them
is not a uniform agreement.

00:38:47.840 --> 00:38:51.380
That doesn't mean it
can't be done for it,

00:38:51.380 --> 00:38:56.780
but it's harder because people
have philosophical views.

00:38:56.780 --> 00:38:59.771
Take the issue of the ACA.

00:38:59.771 --> 00:39:02.270
There are people who agree there
should be many more benefit

00:39:02.270 --> 00:39:04.400
choices that are
available, and others

00:39:04.400 --> 00:39:06.440
who are very afraid
of what that would be.

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:09.900
And so fixing the ACA could
be a very high priority.

00:39:09.900 --> 00:39:11.537
But the second
line is, OK, we're

00:39:11.537 --> 00:39:13.370
going to have a thousand
different policies.

00:39:13.370 --> 00:39:15.920
No, we're going to have
two, and that'll do it.

00:39:15.920 --> 00:39:18.800
So the inability
to agree on the it.

00:39:18.800 --> 00:39:21.740
And I just want to
alert people, this

00:39:21.740 --> 00:39:25.430
is the most poorly
understood about polling.

00:39:25.430 --> 00:39:26.900
People like Medicare forward.

00:39:26.900 --> 00:39:27.890
They like this.

00:39:27.890 --> 00:39:30.960
And then they tell you they
won't pay a dollar in taxes.

00:39:30.960 --> 00:39:35.600
And so unless you confront
people with the actual choice,

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:40.680
a lot of these polls
are not that suggestive.

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:41.480
At the same time--

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:43.040
I'll go back to
this at the end--

00:39:43.040 --> 00:39:47.480
I think the political process
will be unbelievably frustrated

00:39:47.480 --> 00:39:50.450
if two years from now
after people were told

00:39:50.450 --> 00:39:52.730
this election is one the
most pivotal elections

00:39:52.730 --> 00:39:55.970
in American history and
nothing gets passed.

00:39:55.970 --> 00:39:58.490
So I don't want to
have a new cynicism

00:39:58.490 --> 00:40:02.040
scale about everybody's
going to be running in 2020.

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:03.990
Well really, nothing
could be done.

00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:06.620
We ran and we couldn't.

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:10.070
I think something on this
list will have to be done.

00:40:10.070 --> 00:40:12.300
I think there'll be a
great deal of cynicism.

00:40:12.300 --> 00:40:13.880
But then again, I
didn't predict who

00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:15.129
the president was going to be.

00:40:15.129 --> 00:40:16.241
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:16.241 --> 00:40:18.170
MARTY KADY: Well,
let's leave Washington

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:21.890
for a moment on that
note and discuss,

00:40:21.890 --> 00:40:24.770
I know this panel is supposed to
be about the role of Congress.

00:40:24.770 --> 00:40:29.120
We've established the
divisiveness and the gridlock.

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:31.760
So I want to talk a little bit
with each of the panelists,

00:40:31.760 --> 00:40:34.190
if you have just a
moment to weigh in,

00:40:34.190 --> 00:40:35.490
about the role of states.

00:40:35.490 --> 00:40:38.640
States have become real
innovators on policy.

00:40:38.640 --> 00:40:42.440
If you watched Governor
Gavin Newsom's inaugural

00:40:42.440 --> 00:40:46.750
in California, he's proposing
free community college.

00:40:46.750 --> 00:40:49.190
If you look at the
state-by-state actions in K

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:51.354
through 12 education
and in higher ed,

00:40:51.354 --> 00:40:52.520
there's a lot of innovation.

00:40:52.520 --> 00:40:55.220
There's things that are
working in both Republican-run

00:40:55.220 --> 00:40:56.870
and Democratic-run states.

00:40:56.870 --> 00:40:59.630
On health care, I was telling
our panelists beforehand,

00:40:59.630 --> 00:41:01.442
our Politico Pro
policy reporters, we

00:41:01.442 --> 00:41:02.900
have a lot of people
in Washington,

00:41:02.900 --> 00:41:05.750
but we're finding more
interesting stories

00:41:05.750 --> 00:41:09.900
in California, and in New
York, and Florida, and Indiana,

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:12.560
places that are experimenting
with different ways

00:41:12.560 --> 00:41:14.450
to handle the ACA.

00:41:14.450 --> 00:41:18.800
California wants to expand it
but other conservative states

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:21.950
are trying to have work
requirements around Medicaid.

00:41:21.950 --> 00:41:25.617
Indiana has passed one of the
most restrictive abortion laws

00:41:25.617 --> 00:41:27.200
in the country because
they want to be

00:41:27.200 --> 00:41:30.860
the state that makes the
challenge against Roe v. Wade.

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:32.780
So maybe we can do
a quick round robin

00:41:32.780 --> 00:41:34.370
with a few minutes
left here before we

00:41:34.370 --> 00:41:36.800
go to our audience about
what states you're watching

00:41:36.800 --> 00:41:38.840
and should our audience
watch for, like, hey,

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:39.990
Washington is gridlocked.

00:41:39.990 --> 00:41:42.380
Here's what can actually
happen that could prove

00:41:42.380 --> 00:41:44.844
to be a productive policy move.

00:41:44.844 --> 00:41:46.010
I'll start with you, Martin.

00:41:46.010 --> 00:41:47.750
MARTIN WEST: Sure I'll
start with one of the issues

00:41:47.750 --> 00:41:49.900
that you just mentioned, which
is the notion of free community

00:41:49.900 --> 00:41:50.400
college.

00:41:50.400 --> 00:41:52.210
That proposal has been
made in California

00:41:52.210 --> 00:41:54.940
and some other states
by incoming governors.

00:41:54.940 --> 00:42:00.190
What's interesting about it is
that it's a bipartisan issue.

00:42:00.190 --> 00:42:03.160
Leading the charge, Tennessee,
a traditionally conservative

00:42:03.160 --> 00:42:04.070
state.

00:42:04.070 --> 00:42:06.070
And one of the reasons
it's attractive to states

00:42:06.070 --> 00:42:08.110
is because it's relatively
inexpensive to do.

00:42:08.110 --> 00:42:10.570
Community college is
already quite affordable,

00:42:10.570 --> 00:42:12.910
and a Pell grant from
the federal government

00:42:12.910 --> 00:42:16.330
covers much of it
for most students.

00:42:16.330 --> 00:42:18.550
So I think you'll see
continued interest in that.

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:22.120
One concern there is
whether that availability

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:24.490
of a free option might
do some students who

00:42:24.490 --> 00:42:26.500
could have attended a
four-year school to attend

00:42:26.500 --> 00:42:29.710
a two-year school, where
completion rates tend

00:42:29.710 --> 00:42:33.070
to be quite low, and they
might have been better off

00:42:33.070 --> 00:42:34.170
in a four-year option.

00:42:34.170 --> 00:42:36.550
So I think that's
something for policymakers

00:42:36.550 --> 00:42:37.900
to pay attention to.

00:42:37.900 --> 00:42:40.120
More broadly, I think
at the K12 level,

00:42:40.120 --> 00:42:43.960
you have seen some
divergence among states.

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:49.540
There are several states
that have taken various steps

00:42:49.540 --> 00:42:52.990
over the past decade to expand
access to private schools.

00:42:52.990 --> 00:42:55.960
That really is a question
addressed by state policymakers

00:42:55.960 --> 00:42:57.970
rather than the
federal government,

00:42:57.970 --> 00:43:02.290
despite Secretary DeVos'
obvious interest in that.

00:43:02.290 --> 00:43:06.700
And so states like Indiana
Florida, Ohio, Louisiana

00:43:06.700 --> 00:43:10.300
have gone quite aggressively
in that direction.

00:43:10.300 --> 00:43:13.400
More blue states have
avoided that altogether.

00:43:13.400 --> 00:43:16.510
And so there's an interesting
divergence going on

00:43:16.510 --> 00:43:20.590
that we can learn from a
lot going forward, I think.

00:43:20.590 --> 00:43:23.860
Bob, I don't think many
in the charter community

00:43:23.860 --> 00:43:25.810
would have appreciated
your linking

00:43:25.810 --> 00:43:28.390
the notion of charter
schools to private school

00:43:28.390 --> 00:43:31.000
choice in the poll question.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:33.377
Charters have tried to
avoid that debate yet.

00:43:33.377 --> 00:43:34.210
ROBERT BLENDON: Yes.

00:43:34.210 --> 00:43:35.751
MARTIN WEST: And I
think you're going

00:43:35.751 --> 00:43:39.730
to see ramped up conflict over
the role of charter schools.

00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:41.920
There has been a bit of
partisan polarization

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:45.130
on that topic in recent
years, and so that's

00:43:45.130 --> 00:43:47.380
going to be something to
watch going forward as well.

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:49.480
MARTY KADY: I'd like to just
jump over to Sheila real quick.

00:43:49.480 --> 00:43:50.830
We've got about a minute here.

00:43:50.830 --> 00:43:54.550
Are there particular state
moves on Medicaid or ACA

00:43:54.550 --> 00:43:56.800
that we should be watching
that will tell us something

00:43:56.800 --> 00:43:59.566
about where things are headed?

00:43:59.566 --> 00:44:02.080
SHEILA BURKE: I think,
Marty, as you suggested,

00:44:02.080 --> 00:44:04.450
there are a host of
things taking place.

00:44:04.450 --> 00:44:07.760
Certainly, Wisconsin is an
interesting state to watch.

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:10.630
It's looking to expand
its Medicaid program.

00:44:10.630 --> 00:44:13.810
Colorado and New
Mexico are both states

00:44:13.810 --> 00:44:16.420
that are looking to increase
opportunities for coverage

00:44:16.420 --> 00:44:19.330
and are looking at public
options and expansion

00:44:19.330 --> 00:44:21.460
I think we also need
to watch what the state

00:44:21.460 --> 00:44:24.760
insurance commissioners you're
doing in a variety of states,

00:44:24.760 --> 00:44:27.820
some of whom are trying to
prevent the kind of changes

00:44:27.820 --> 00:44:31.300
that a short-term plan
might result in in terms

00:44:31.300 --> 00:44:34.090
of their risk pools and
essentially drawing people out

00:44:34.090 --> 00:44:35.950
of the ACA plans.

00:44:35.950 --> 00:44:39.980
Obviously, California, as usual,
leading a series of efforts,

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:41.650
including wanting
to provide coverage

00:44:41.650 --> 00:44:44.590
for undocumented immigrants.

00:44:44.590 --> 00:44:46.330
And that is
similarly, you've got

00:44:46.330 --> 00:44:48.460
that taking place in New
York, both in the city

00:44:48.460 --> 00:44:50.330
as well as in the state.

00:44:50.330 --> 00:44:52.390
So I think there are really
a host of activities.

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:54.280
Arkansas, of course,
has led the effort

00:44:54.280 --> 00:44:56.050
on the work requirements.

00:44:56.050 --> 00:44:57.910
We're now looking at
data that's suggesting

00:44:57.910 --> 00:45:00.950
close to 18,000 people
will have lost coverage.

00:45:00.950 --> 00:45:03.280
So I think they're really,
each of the states, either

00:45:03.280 --> 00:45:06.520
in Medicaid, either to expand,
or the work requirement

00:45:06.520 --> 00:45:09.430
issues, other waiver requests
that are coming forward

00:45:09.430 --> 00:45:12.490
from a number of states
in terms of flexibility

00:45:12.490 --> 00:45:14.350
under the 1115 waivers.

00:45:14.350 --> 00:45:16.600
And I think we also have
to keep an eye on what

00:45:16.600 --> 00:45:18.200
the Feds are willing to do.

00:45:18.200 --> 00:45:19.840
That is, what the
administration is

00:45:19.840 --> 00:45:22.030
willing to allow to go forward.

00:45:22.030 --> 00:45:24.850
And there's another court case
before the Supreme Court, which

00:45:24.850 --> 00:45:26.680
is quite interesting,
which is looking

00:45:26.680 --> 00:45:30.340
at CMS' authority with
respect to its regulations,

00:45:30.340 --> 00:45:32.290
and its pronouncements,
and what has

00:45:32.290 --> 00:45:34.750
to go through a
public comment period.

00:45:34.750 --> 00:45:37.150
So again, I think there is
a great deal taking place

00:45:37.150 --> 00:45:38.373
at the state level.

00:45:38.373 --> 00:45:39.910
MARTY KADY: Well, thank you.

00:45:39.910 --> 00:45:41.890
The Arkansas case is
an interesting example

00:45:41.890 --> 00:45:44.050
of what sounds good on paper.

00:45:44.050 --> 00:45:47.590
Let's have work requirements, if
you're especially conservative,

00:45:47.590 --> 00:45:49.960
for Medicaid, and
then 18,000 people

00:45:49.960 --> 00:45:51.112
end up getting kicked off.

00:45:51.112 --> 00:45:52.570
I don't know if
they intended that,

00:45:52.570 --> 00:45:54.269
but that's been the consequence.

00:45:54.269 --> 00:45:55.810
We're going to jump
to some questions

00:45:55.810 --> 00:45:58.030
from both our online
audience. and if we have time,

00:45:58.030 --> 00:46:00.839
folks in our live audience
can ask a question or two.

00:46:00.839 --> 00:46:02.380
There is one question
about the poll,

00:46:02.380 --> 00:46:04.360
and I'm glad this is
in here, because it's

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:05.390
an interesting one.

00:46:05.390 --> 00:46:08.380
It said the majority
of Democrats

00:46:08.380 --> 00:46:10.547
want to repeal and
replace the ACA.

00:46:10.547 --> 00:46:12.880
When you pause and say, wait
a second, that's not right,

00:46:12.880 --> 00:46:15.310
it's because they want
something bigger, Medicare

00:46:15.310 --> 00:46:21.340
for all, single-payer,
maybe a European-style plan.

00:46:21.340 --> 00:46:24.729
Bob, can you talk about what the
poll revealed on that question?

00:46:24.729 --> 00:46:26.270
That is a question
from our audience.

00:46:26.270 --> 00:46:28.360
ROBERT BLENDON: So
a terrific question.

00:46:28.360 --> 00:46:30.490
How can you have people
incredibly in favor

00:46:30.490 --> 00:46:32.240
of something for repealing it?

00:46:32.240 --> 00:46:34.530
So it turns out an
accident of the poll

00:46:34.530 --> 00:46:37.660
is if I want something bigger,
I have no way to say that.

00:46:37.660 --> 00:46:41.990
So we looked at the second poll
we did, and the results are.

00:46:41.990 --> 00:46:46.045
If a Democrat said, I want
repeal and replace, almost 80%

00:46:46.045 --> 00:46:48.530
wanted Medicare for all.

00:46:48.530 --> 00:46:50.450
They wanted universal coverage.

00:46:50.450 --> 00:46:54.680
What they were saying is the
ACA is too anemic as it is.

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:56.040
I need something bigger.

00:46:56.040 --> 00:46:57.610
But we only gave
them one question.

00:46:57.610 --> 00:47:01.250
So Republicans were answering,
I want this thing shrunken.

00:47:01.250 --> 00:47:04.160
I want a lot of conservatives--
and the Democrats in it

00:47:04.160 --> 00:47:06.470
wanted to have a debate
over Medicare for all.

00:47:06.470 --> 00:47:09.980
So we really in the future
need to split that out.

00:47:09.980 --> 00:47:12.924
When you say that I want
an alternative to the ACA,

00:47:12.924 --> 00:47:14.840
do you really want
something larger and bigger

00:47:14.840 --> 00:47:16.490
that covers everybody,
or do you really

00:47:16.490 --> 00:47:18.400
want something much
more restricted?

00:47:18.400 --> 00:47:20.210
But our apologies to everybody.

00:47:20.210 --> 00:47:23.660
We've got numerous
emails about, my neighbor

00:47:23.660 --> 00:47:27.050
is furiously in love
with Medicare for all

00:47:27.050 --> 00:47:29.390
and said they wanted
to repeal the ACA.

00:47:29.390 --> 00:47:30.830
Could you clarify that?

00:47:30.830 --> 00:47:32.542
We have.

00:47:32.542 --> 00:47:35.450
MARTY KADY: There's
a specific question

00:47:35.450 --> 00:47:38.480
from an online participant
here who didn't

00:47:38.480 --> 00:47:40.052
provide their name for Richard.

00:47:40.052 --> 00:47:42.510
I don't want to duplicate what
you've already talked about,

00:47:42.510 --> 00:47:44.720
but this person is asking,
since reducing drug prices

00:47:44.720 --> 00:47:49.100
is an area of consensus, what
is the first actionable steps

00:47:49.100 --> 00:47:49.600
we'll see?

00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:52.200
I know you addressed some
of the legislative options,

00:47:52.200 --> 00:47:55.397
but if there's something
specific that people out there

00:47:55.397 --> 00:47:57.230
should see as a signal
that there's actually

00:47:57.230 --> 00:47:58.620
something happening on this.

00:47:58.620 --> 00:47:59.453
RICHARD FRANK: Yeah.

00:47:59.453 --> 00:48:03.470
I think you're going to
see a lot more being done

00:48:03.470 --> 00:48:07.010
both in legislation, regulation,
to get generics on the market

00:48:07.010 --> 00:48:09.650
quicker, to get
biosimilars on the market,

00:48:09.650 --> 00:48:12.290
to just really amp
up competition.

00:48:12.290 --> 00:48:17.400
I think everybody agrees
that that's a good thing.

00:48:17.400 --> 00:48:24.326
And we've seen that when you do
that, prices continue to fall.

00:48:24.326 --> 00:48:26.170
MARTY KADY: And one
for you, Martin.

00:48:26.170 --> 00:48:28.910
It's from one of our
online participants.

00:48:28.910 --> 00:48:31.040
The question is, given
the student debt crisis,

00:48:31.040 --> 00:48:33.577
community colleges become
increasingly more attractive,

00:48:33.577 --> 00:48:34.910
but it's still really expensive.

00:48:34.910 --> 00:48:37.220
What would have to be
done at the federal level

00:48:37.220 --> 00:48:39.500
to make a difference
in increasing access?

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:42.200
This poll shows people
are in favor of it,

00:48:42.200 --> 00:48:44.150
but is there any
collaboration you

00:48:44.150 --> 00:48:46.190
see between the
Republican worldview

00:48:46.190 --> 00:48:47.560
and the Democratic worldview?

00:48:47.560 --> 00:48:50.550
And you mentioned a lot of
the folks on that video,

00:48:50.550 --> 00:48:54.380
I don't know what their higher
education background was.

00:48:54.380 --> 00:48:56.822
But some of them didn't
look like they had just

00:48:56.822 --> 00:48:58.280
graduated from a
four-year college,

00:48:58.280 --> 00:49:00.950
maybe had gone for master's,
taken some community college,

00:49:00.950 --> 00:49:02.900
or for-profits.

00:49:02.900 --> 00:49:04.730
But can you try to
address this question?

00:49:04.730 --> 00:49:05.720
MARTIN WEST: Yeah.

00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:07.640
A community college
option is usually

00:49:07.640 --> 00:49:10.440
quite an affordable
one, contrary to what

00:49:10.440 --> 00:49:11.720
the question suggests.

00:49:11.720 --> 00:49:14.790
Now, there is the difficult
issue of living expenses.

00:49:14.790 --> 00:49:19.880
And it may be possible to
provide additional support

00:49:19.880 --> 00:49:22.100
for students as they are
going through the school

00:49:22.100 --> 00:49:24.800
beyond tuition.

00:49:24.800 --> 00:49:32.990
But I think that's where
you'll see states trying

00:49:32.990 --> 00:49:37.100
to innovate through the
free community-type programs

00:49:37.100 --> 00:49:39.620
that I was mentioning
a moment ago.

00:49:39.620 --> 00:49:42.950
I think, from a federal
policy perspective,

00:49:42.950 --> 00:49:45.950
the Pell Grant system is
relatively well-established.

00:49:45.950 --> 00:49:48.390
There is question about
who exactly is eligible

00:49:48.390 --> 00:49:50.600
and how you certify
your eligibility, how

00:49:50.600 --> 00:49:52.880
we can simplify that for
students and make sure

00:49:52.880 --> 00:49:55.250
that process is not a barrier.

00:49:55.250 --> 00:49:58.490
But I think the real question
is, how do we give schools

00:49:58.490 --> 00:50:01.471
some skin in the game when
it comes to student results,

00:50:01.471 --> 00:50:01.970
right?

00:50:01.970 --> 00:50:05.720
And I think finding
a way to hold

00:50:05.720 --> 00:50:08.050
them accountable
for their student

00:50:08.050 --> 00:50:10.400
success in repaying
their loans has to be

00:50:10.400 --> 00:50:11.800
part of that conversation.

00:50:11.800 --> 00:50:13.580
And I think members
of both parties

00:50:13.580 --> 00:50:17.780
have come around to that
view, sometimes reluctantly.

00:50:17.780 --> 00:50:19.430
The Obama administration
really tried

00:50:19.430 --> 00:50:21.590
to advance that cause
through something

00:50:21.590 --> 00:50:23.840
known as the gainful
employment rules, which

00:50:23.840 --> 00:50:26.060
said that career-focused
programs mostly

00:50:26.060 --> 00:50:29.120
in the for-profit
sector might lose

00:50:29.120 --> 00:50:31.730
their eligibility for
federal financial aid

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:34.130
if their students weren't
successful in repaying

00:50:34.130 --> 00:50:35.580
their loans.

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:37.100
There's been a
lot of controversy

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:40.100
around that proposal,
questions about its legality,

00:50:40.100 --> 00:50:41.300
its feasibility.

00:50:41.300 --> 00:50:44.270
The Davos administration--
the Trump administration,

00:50:44.270 --> 00:50:48.350
Secretary Davos, has
repealed that approach,

00:50:48.350 --> 00:50:52.260
and I think that's where the
action will be going forward.

00:50:52.260 --> 00:50:54.260
I think the key step
will be to make sure

00:50:54.260 --> 00:50:58.340
that it applies to all colleges,
including community colleges,

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:00.981
rather than appearing to single
out the for-profit sector,

00:51:00.981 --> 00:51:03.230
which I think was one of the
challenges with the Obama

00:51:03.230 --> 00:51:03.935
approach.

00:51:03.935 --> 00:51:06.050
MARTY KADY: I want to put in
a plug for a Politico story.

00:51:06.050 --> 00:51:07.330
We mentioned that
Gavin Newsom, who

00:51:07.330 --> 00:51:09.560
is a governor of one of the more
liberal states in the country,

00:51:09.560 --> 00:51:10.730
is pushing free
community college.

00:51:10.730 --> 00:51:12.380
But we had a recent
story in Politico

00:51:12.380 --> 00:51:16.890
about a community college
in eastern Tennessee,

00:51:16.890 --> 00:51:20.240
which is a place that Trump
won by 40 or 50 points that

00:51:20.240 --> 00:51:22.910
has long had free
community college.

00:51:22.910 --> 00:51:25.490
The name of the college is
slipping, but look it up.

00:51:25.490 --> 00:51:27.500
It's a really interesting
story on a policy

00:51:27.500 --> 00:51:29.720
that is working in a
different part of the country.

00:51:29.720 --> 00:51:32.590
I'm going to throw a
question to Sheila here.

00:51:32.590 --> 00:51:35.390
It's from Joyce Friedan, who is
a news editor at MedPage Today.

00:51:35.390 --> 00:51:36.925
Hi, Joyce.

00:51:36.925 --> 00:51:39.050
Any thoughts on what might
happen with the Medicaid

00:51:39.050 --> 00:51:39.750
program?

00:51:39.750 --> 00:51:42.170
She's specifically asking about
whether the administration

00:51:42.170 --> 00:51:44.030
or congressional
Republicans will push

00:51:44.030 --> 00:51:46.670
for block granting Medicaid.

00:51:46.670 --> 00:51:50.660
That's a long-term
conservative priority block

00:51:50.660 --> 00:51:52.850
granting federal
money so that states

00:51:52.850 --> 00:51:55.700
can put their own ideological
imprint on it is something

00:51:55.700 --> 00:51:56.960
they love to do with Medicaid.

00:51:56.960 --> 00:51:58.710
Can you take that question?

00:51:58.710 --> 00:51:59.960
SHEILA BURKE: Sure, thank you.

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:01.700
It's a terrific question.

00:52:01.700 --> 00:52:04.106
There has been a very
recent story suggesting

00:52:04.106 --> 00:52:05.480
that the administration
was going

00:52:05.480 --> 00:52:08.960
to allow states to essentially
seek through a waiver process

00:52:08.960 --> 00:52:11.750
the ability to block
grant and give them

00:52:11.750 --> 00:52:14.360
full flexibility in terms of
the design of their Medicaid

00:52:14.360 --> 00:52:15.140
program.

00:52:15.140 --> 00:52:18.320
The other form of this
is a per capita cap.

00:52:18.320 --> 00:52:22.760
Both are resisted tremendously
by Democrats, a fear

00:52:22.760 --> 00:52:24.980
that the program, in
fact, will not only

00:52:24.980 --> 00:52:27.770
change its nature because
of the state's flexibility

00:52:27.770 --> 00:52:30.410
around issues like
eligibility, but also

00:52:30.410 --> 00:52:34.580
that the funds over time will
be an adequate cover the folks

00:52:34.580 --> 00:52:36.900
that are currently
covered under the program.

00:52:36.900 --> 00:52:40.010
So I fully expect that there
will be continued pressure

00:52:40.010 --> 00:52:42.140
on the part of
Republicans to pursue that

00:52:42.140 --> 00:52:45.660
or to allow the states to do
it through a waiver process,

00:52:45.660 --> 00:52:48.980
but I think it will continue
to be fought tooth and nail

00:52:48.980 --> 00:52:52.820
by the constituencies over
the entitlement program

00:52:52.820 --> 00:52:56.630
nature of Medicaid, and also
those states, essentially,

00:52:56.630 --> 00:52:59.480
who are likely to lessen
the number of things

00:52:59.480 --> 00:53:02.630
that are provided and lessen
the coverage writ large.

00:53:02.630 --> 00:53:04.330
But I assume it will
come back up again.

00:53:04.330 --> 00:53:07.100
MARTY KADY: There is a
question on drug prices

00:53:07.100 --> 00:53:09.140
from our online audience.

00:53:09.140 --> 00:53:11.150
What can be done to
lower drug prices

00:53:11.150 --> 00:53:13.100
by reducing risk
and inefficiency

00:53:13.100 --> 00:53:14.390
in drug development?

00:53:14.390 --> 00:53:18.440
For example, this questioner
says that 90% of new drugs

00:53:18.440 --> 00:53:21.150
fail in phase 3 clinical trials.

00:53:21.150 --> 00:53:24.470
So what is the improvement
that could happen

00:53:24.470 --> 00:53:25.670
during the clinical process?

00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:27.530
I don't know if that
statistic is correct,

00:53:27.530 --> 00:53:28.952
but you can correct as you go.

00:53:28.952 --> 00:53:30.410
But that's an
interesting question.

00:53:30.410 --> 00:53:32.520
A lot of the cost is
built into the process,

00:53:32.520 --> 00:53:34.115
not just at the retail end.

00:53:34.115 --> 00:53:35.210
RICHARD FRANK: Yeah.

00:53:35.210 --> 00:53:41.090
And this is not a
place to necessarily

00:53:41.090 --> 00:53:43.550
be super optimistic.

00:53:43.550 --> 00:53:46.160
Most of the cost of
the clinical trials

00:53:46.160 --> 00:53:48.450
comes from human testing.

00:53:48.450 --> 00:53:53.960
And as you get more and more
towards personalized medicine,

00:53:53.960 --> 00:54:02.150
as you get more granular
in your clinical targets,

00:54:02.150 --> 00:54:06.350
unless you have huge
impacts on the disease,

00:54:06.350 --> 00:54:07.760
you need very large samples.

00:54:07.760 --> 00:54:12.440
You need to do big tests,
and that's expensive.

00:54:12.440 --> 00:54:17.060
And the combination of
having these targets

00:54:17.060 --> 00:54:22.980
and having these
dramatic testing needs

00:54:22.980 --> 00:54:26.100
does not leave me
optimistic on that front.

00:54:26.100 --> 00:54:30.290
I do think that artificial
intelligence, some

00:54:30.290 --> 00:54:32.610
of the big data things
that we're seeing offer

00:54:32.610 --> 00:54:35.840
some opportunity to
shave some costs,

00:54:35.840 --> 00:54:40.220
but I don't see a clear path
right now to dramatic changes

00:54:40.220 --> 00:54:41.795
there.

00:54:41.795 --> 00:54:43.850
MARTY KADY: We're going
to do some wrap-up here.

00:54:43.850 --> 00:54:45.590
We have about four
minutes to go.

00:54:45.590 --> 00:54:51.350
And I'll ask each panelist
to give a quick takeaway

00:54:51.350 --> 00:54:52.820
on our discussion.

00:54:52.820 --> 00:54:54.830
Feel free to make any
bold predictions that

00:54:54.830 --> 00:54:57.230
are sure to be wrong,
since we're on tape.

00:54:57.230 --> 00:54:59.615
I'll start with you, Sheila.

00:54:59.615 --> 00:55:03.260
SHEILA BURKE: So I think your
suggestion, bold predictions,

00:55:03.260 --> 00:55:06.440
I think the question is
really what's unknown.

00:55:06.440 --> 00:55:08.450
I think we have to
anticipate that there

00:55:08.450 --> 00:55:11.180
will be either actions on the
part of the administration

00:55:11.180 --> 00:55:14.810
on a regulatory basis or
an administrative basis

00:55:14.810 --> 00:55:16.910
that we can't predict
today that could have

00:55:16.910 --> 00:55:19.250
some enormous impacts
on either the Medicaid

00:55:19.250 --> 00:55:21.590
program or the Medicare program.

00:55:21.590 --> 00:55:24.410
I think it's a two-year
period of time where

00:55:24.410 --> 00:55:27.710
there is deep division,
as Bob has suggested,

00:55:27.710 --> 00:55:30.900
with little where one sees
the opportunity for coming

00:55:30.900 --> 00:55:31.400
together.

00:55:31.400 --> 00:55:34.530
Drug prices may be
one of those areas.

00:55:34.530 --> 00:55:37.160
But I worry that, in fact,
we will make little progress

00:55:37.160 --> 00:55:39.170
on some of the other
broad health care issues

00:55:39.170 --> 00:55:41.570
about which we are
concerned because

00:55:41.570 --> 00:55:43.550
of that fundamental
disagreement as to what

00:55:43.550 --> 00:55:45.710
the role of the
government should be.

00:55:45.710 --> 00:55:48.140
But I'm expecting and
looking forward to the states

00:55:48.140 --> 00:55:51.750
testing out a lot of things,
positively, one hopes,

00:55:51.750 --> 00:55:54.290
in terms of providing
services and making

00:55:54.290 --> 00:55:55.700
things more affordable.

00:55:55.700 --> 00:55:57.170
MARTY KADY: Martin?

00:55:57.170 --> 00:55:58.520
MARTIN WEST: Sure.

00:55:58.520 --> 00:56:02.540
So I guess one prediction going
forward, as we're sitting here,

00:56:02.540 --> 00:56:05.030
teachers in the nation's
second largest school system,

00:56:05.030 --> 00:56:06.830
Los Angeles Unified,
have recently

00:56:06.830 --> 00:56:09.380
wrapped up a week-long strike.

00:56:09.380 --> 00:56:11.630
Teachers in Denver
have just voted

00:56:11.630 --> 00:56:13.140
to authorize a
strike of their own.

00:56:13.140 --> 00:56:15.740
This comes on the heels
of statewide walkouts

00:56:15.740 --> 00:56:18.800
in six states, including some
quite conservative states

00:56:18.800 --> 00:56:20.420
last spring.

00:56:20.420 --> 00:56:22.040
I think there's
a lot of activism

00:56:22.040 --> 00:56:24.410
around the issue of school
spending and teacher salaries

00:56:24.410 --> 00:56:29.300
right now, and I expect
that to continue.

00:56:29.300 --> 00:56:31.460
Public sector unions,
including teachers unions

00:56:31.460 --> 00:56:34.850
recently lost the ability
to collect agency fees

00:56:34.850 --> 00:56:38.030
from nonmembers for their
representation services.

00:56:38.030 --> 00:56:40.860
They're out there really trying
to demonstrate their value.

00:56:40.860 --> 00:56:43.820
And so I think you will
see continued activism

00:56:43.820 --> 00:56:45.290
on that front.

00:56:45.290 --> 00:56:49.100
One last observation, I
was wondering about my role

00:56:49.100 --> 00:56:51.410
on this panel and
why it made sense

00:56:51.410 --> 00:56:56.540
to have one education person
alongside multiple health care

00:56:56.540 --> 00:56:57.110
people.

00:56:57.110 --> 00:57:00.140
I do think there is a natural
connection between the two

00:57:00.140 --> 00:57:01.820
issues, however.

00:57:01.820 --> 00:57:04.670
And that's because this question
of controlling health care

00:57:04.670 --> 00:57:06.470
costs, which came
up in the polling,

00:57:06.470 --> 00:57:10.500
is one that matters for health
care and also for education.

00:57:10.500 --> 00:57:13.700
If we look at why states
have reduced their investment

00:57:13.700 --> 00:57:16.010
in higher education
on a per-student basis

00:57:16.010 --> 00:57:18.145
in the past few
decades, the key driver

00:57:18.145 --> 00:57:19.520
seems to be that
they're spending

00:57:19.520 --> 00:57:21.060
a lot more on Medicaid.

00:57:21.060 --> 00:57:24.560
So I'm not an expert on the
health care cost control front,

00:57:24.560 --> 00:57:27.170
but I hope you all
can do a good job,

00:57:27.170 --> 00:57:29.014
because it will matter
a lot for those of us

00:57:29.014 --> 00:57:29.930
who work in education.

00:57:29.930 --> 00:57:31.526
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:31.526 --> 00:57:34.200
SHEILA BURKE: And actually,
Marty, if I could just add one

00:57:34.200 --> 00:57:38.005
note to that point, and that
is the link between education

00:57:38.005 --> 00:57:39.360
and health care.

00:57:39.360 --> 00:57:41.240
And we know that the
social determinants

00:57:41.240 --> 00:57:43.970
of health care and the
contributors education

00:57:43.970 --> 00:57:45.920
is an enormously
important factor

00:57:45.920 --> 00:57:48.800
in terms of people's access
to services and people's

00:57:48.800 --> 00:57:49.710
understanding.

00:57:49.710 --> 00:57:52.250
So there is a real
linkage there in terms

00:57:52.250 --> 00:57:53.870
of how to make
services available

00:57:53.870 --> 00:57:56.640
and how people take
up those services

00:57:56.640 --> 00:57:59.570
MARTY KADY: Richard, any
quick wrap-ups or predictions

00:57:59.570 --> 00:58:00.280
for this year?

00:58:00.280 --> 00:58:01.613
RICHARD FRANK: Yeah, two things.

00:58:01.613 --> 00:58:05.150
I think that we
all are clamoring,

00:58:05.150 --> 00:58:08.600
and the public's
clamoring for quick action

00:58:08.600 --> 00:58:09.830
on drugs and things.

00:58:09.830 --> 00:58:13.760
I think it's important to
have a new conversation.

00:58:13.760 --> 00:58:16.529
This has been lying dormant
for about seven years

00:58:16.529 --> 00:58:18.320
since we had the last
serious conversation.

00:58:18.320 --> 00:58:22.010
I think that there are huge
problems in Medicare's drug

00:58:22.010 --> 00:58:26.430
program that will be
important to address.

00:58:26.430 --> 00:58:28.760
And I think having a
conversation about how

00:58:28.760 --> 00:58:31.220
to do that, the
negotiation issue,

00:58:31.220 --> 00:58:34.940
putting down on the
table what the ideas are,

00:58:34.940 --> 00:58:38.060
and vetting them carefully,
I think it's important.

00:58:38.060 --> 00:58:42.770
Just on one last point,
which is slightly different,

00:58:42.770 --> 00:58:44.780
I think one of the
areas that showed up

00:58:44.780 --> 00:58:49.820
in Bob's poll that also shows
up in the state federal nexus

00:58:49.820 --> 00:58:52.490
is addressing the
opioid problem.

00:58:52.490 --> 00:58:57.140
And I think there is enormous
bipartisan opportunity there.

00:58:57.140 --> 00:59:00.140
And I think leveraging
all the tools

00:59:00.140 --> 00:59:02.690
we have at both the state
and the federal level

00:59:02.690 --> 00:59:08.870
is incredibly urgent
to do and really should

00:59:08.870 --> 00:59:12.932
be the major responsibility
of this Congress.

00:59:12.932 --> 00:59:14.390
MARTY KADY: Bob,
you're the one who

00:59:14.390 --> 00:59:16.770
monitors trend lines in polls.

00:59:16.770 --> 00:59:18.020
Where do you see things going?

00:59:18.020 --> 00:59:20.120
ROBERT BLENDON: So
most practical takeaway

00:59:20.120 --> 00:59:24.140
is six months from now,
the leaders of the parties

00:59:24.140 --> 00:59:25.580
are going to go
off by themselves,

00:59:25.580 --> 00:59:27.163
and they're going
to ask one question.

00:59:27.163 --> 00:59:30.350
Do we want to run in
2020 having done nothing?

00:59:30.350 --> 00:59:33.890
And President Trump's going
to have to look in the mirror

00:59:33.890 --> 00:59:36.860
and say, what did
I actually enact?

00:59:36.860 --> 00:59:39.230
And so where there's a big
difference about the future

00:59:39.230 --> 00:59:43.220
is I think you can't be alone in
that room and say, do nothing.

00:59:43.220 --> 00:59:45.860
I think something
here has to happen,

00:59:45.860 --> 00:59:47.450
that you actually
go back to people

00:59:47.450 --> 00:59:50.360
and say, this just
wasn't a sabbatical.

00:59:50.360 --> 00:59:51.740
We did something here.

00:59:51.740 --> 00:59:54.320
But others will
write tomorrow, no.

00:59:54.320 --> 00:59:57.500
The best advantage is to hold
hearings and investigations

00:59:57.500 --> 00:59:58.550
and go home.

00:59:58.550 --> 01:00:00.420
I just think some
of these issues,

01:00:00.420 --> 01:00:02.240
whether it's education
or drug prices,

01:00:02.240 --> 01:00:04.250
they're actually going
to have to act on,

01:00:04.250 --> 01:00:07.610
because the cynicism
of voters, that you

01:00:07.610 --> 01:00:09.980
ran on these
dramatic discussions

01:00:09.980 --> 01:00:12.690
and nothing happened, is
going to be very, very hard.

01:00:12.690 --> 01:00:14.669
But that's a
prediction of someone

01:00:14.669 --> 01:00:16.085
who's been wrong
quite frequently.

01:00:16.085 --> 01:00:17.870
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:17.870 --> 01:00:20.390
MARTY KADY: Well I'm a
Washington journalist,

01:00:20.390 --> 01:00:24.290
so I'm trying not to do
any predictions after 2016.

01:00:24.290 --> 01:00:26.180
So I don't know what's
in the Mueller report

01:00:26.180 --> 01:00:28.880
or what will be in it, I don't
know when the shutdown will end

01:00:28.880 --> 01:00:30.800
or how it will end,
and I don't know

01:00:30.800 --> 01:00:33.260
what the economy will
be like a year from now

01:00:33.260 --> 01:00:35.660
when Democratic voters are
going to the Iowa caucus

01:00:35.660 --> 01:00:39.260
and deciding among 30 to
40 Democratic candidates.

01:00:39.260 --> 01:00:41.180
But do know that
those three things

01:00:41.180 --> 01:00:44.240
will be the cloud over
these substantive issues

01:00:44.240 --> 01:00:48.260
as we roll through the
next six, 12, 18 months.

01:00:48.260 --> 01:00:49.550
We're going to wrap up here.

01:00:49.550 --> 01:00:53.030
On behalf of the
Harvard TH Chan School

01:00:53.030 --> 01:00:55.190
of Public Health
and Politico, I'd

01:00:55.190 --> 01:00:57.260
like to thank
everyone for coming,

01:00:57.260 --> 01:00:58.860
and thank you to
our online audience.

01:00:58.860 --> 01:01:02.580
I'd like to put in a
